.TH UNTAR(1),User Commands,UNTAR(1)

.SH NAME
untar - extract files from a ustar archive

.SH SYNOPSIS
untar [-h] archive ...

.SH DESCRIPTION
untar extracts each named archive into the current directory.
Archives must be in plain ustar format;
compressed archives (.tar.gz, .tar.bz2) are not supported.

For each archive, untar prints a line per entry indicating whether the entry is a regular file, directory, or an ignored special type, then extracts regular files and directories under their recorded paths.

Parent directories are created as needed.

The following tar entry types are skipped with a message:

1: hardlink

2: symlink

3: character device

4: block device

6: FIFO

Entries of type 5 (directory) are created;
all other types are treated as regular files.

Checksums are verified for every 512-byte header block.
A mismatch terminates extraction of that archive.

.SH OPTIONS
-h: Print a short usage summary and exit 0.

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
untar: Unable to open FILE - a named archive could not be opened.

untar: Short read on FILE: expected 512, got N - the archive ended mid-block.

untar: Checksum failure - a header block's checksum did not match.

untar: Could not create directory PATH - mkdir failed even after creating parents.

untar: Failed write - a write to an output file failed.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: Always.
Errors are reported but do not change the exit status.

.SH SEE ALSO
cp(1), mkdir(1)
